{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "CLMUAtmosphere",
        "description": "Atmospheric interface for the Community Land Model Urban (CLMU) parameterization, following Chapter 1 of Oleson et al. (2010). Computes three diagnostic outputs from atmospheric forcing inputs: atmospheric vapor pressure (e_atm = q_atm P_atm / (epsilon + (1-epsilon) q_atm)), atmospheric air density (rho_atm = (P_atm - (1-epsilon) e_atm) / (R_da T_atm)), and the reference height for flux computations (z_atm = z_prime_atm + z_0 + z_d). Here epsilon = MW_wv/MW_da = 0.622 is the molecular-weight ratio of water vapor to dry air, and R_da = R_gas/MW_da is the specific gas constant for dry air. The urban canyon is represented as a roof + sunlit/shaded wall + pervious/impervious road five-column system; this component defines the atmospheric forcing interface that the rest of the canopy column reads. Migrated from UrbanCanopy.jl@9200edd4 src/clmu_introduction.jl:22 (`CLMUAtmosphere` @component). Parameterized as observed-only: forcings (q_atm, P_atm, T_atm, z_prime_atm, z_0, z_d, etc.) are inputs (parameters); e_atm, rho_atm, z_atm are the algebraic state outputs.",
        "tags": [
            "urban_canopy",
            "clmu",
            "atmosphere",
            "interface",
            "observed-only"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-12T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "UrbanCanopy.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-hf1c)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Oleson, K. W., G. B. Bonan, J. J. Feddema, M. Vertenstein, and E. Kluzek (2010). Technical Description of an Urban Parameterization for the Community Land Model (CLMU). NCAR Technical Note NCAR/TN-480+STR. Chapter 1 (Introduction and atmospheric forcing), Table 1.1 (forcing inputs), Table 1.3 (surface parameters, Footnote 1 p.16), Table 1.4 (physical constants, p.25), pp. 16-17."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Oke, T. R. (1987). Boundary Layer Climates, 2nd ed. Routledge, London — for the urban-canyon geometry referenced in Oleson et al. (2010) Chapter 1."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "CLMUAtmosphere": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: UrbanCanopy.jl@9200edd4f15609f20339d3a7d104de8064544310:src/clmu_introduction.jl:22\nUpstream `CLMUAtmosphere` is an MTK `@component` with two `@constants` blocks (4 base constants + 4 derived constants), two `@parameters` blocks (14 atmospheric forcing inputs + 2 surface parameters), three time-indexed `@variables` (e_atm, rho_atm, z_atm), and three algebraic equations (no derivatives). Identical equation structure preserved here.\n\nConstants encoding (mirrors surface_energy_flux.esm/heat_flux.esm/heating_cooling_flux.esm sibling pattern of encoding upstream `@constants` as fixed-default parameters so the units flow through the unit checker): the four base constants from Oleson Table 1.4 (kappa_boltz = 1.38065e-23 J/K Boltzmann, N_A = 6.02214e23 /mol Avogadro, MW_da = 0.028966 kg/mol dry-air molecular weight, MW_wv = 0.018016 kg/mol water-vapor molecular weight) are encoded with their upstream defaults; the four derived constants (R_gas = N_A * kappa_boltz = 8.314467591 J/(K*mol) universal gas constant, R_da = R_gas / MW_da = 287.0423113650487 J/(K*kg) dry-air specific gas constant, epsilon_ratio = MW_wv/MW_da = 0.6219705862045157 dimensionless, one_minus_epsilon = 1 - MW_wv/MW_da = 0.37802941379548427 dimensionless) are encoded with their IEEE-754-double-precision pre-computed values from those bases. The pre-computed values are exactly what Julia computes for the same `@constants` expressions at MTK macro-expansion time, so the diagnostic outputs match the upstream test fixtures bit-for-bit (e.g. e_atm at q=0.01, P=101325 is 1619.2546136658295 Pa in both this ESM and the upstream test).\n\nGreek-to-ASCII identifier renaming (rig convention, matches surface_energy_flux.esm σ_SB → sigma_SB / ε_g → epsilon_g / λE_g → lambdaE_g, and snow_density.esm rho_*): upstream `κ_boltz` → `kappa_boltz`, `ε_ratio` → `epsilon_ratio`, `one_minus_ε` → `one_minus_epsilon`, `θ_atm` → `theta_atm`, `ρ_atm` → `rho_atm`. ASCII identifiers (`N_A`, `MW_da`, `MW_wv`, `R_gas`, `R_da`, `e_atm`, `z_atm`, `q_atm`, `P_atm`, `T_atm`, `z_prime_atm`, `u_atm`, `v_atm`, `q_rain`, `q_sno`, `L_atm_down`, `S_atm_*`, `z_0`, `z_d`) are preserved verbatim.\n\nAtmospheric-forcing parameters preserved: the upstream component declares 14 forcing parameters from Oleson Table 1.1 (wind components u_atm/v_atm, potential temperature theta_atm, specific humidity q_atm, pressure P_atm, temperature T_atm, downward longwave L_atm_down, precip q_rain/q_sno, direct/diffuse vis/nir solar fluxes S_atm_dir_vis/S_atm_dir_nir/S_atm_dif_vis/S_atm_dif_nir, and the model-provided reference height z_prime_atm) plus 2 surface parameters from Table 1.3 Footnote 1 (z_0 roughness length, z_d displacement height). Only q_atm, P_atm, T_atm, z_prime_atm, z_0, z_d, epsilon_ratio, one_minus_epsilon, R_da appear in the 3 diagnostic equations; the remaining forcing inputs (u_atm, v_atm, theta_atm, L_atm_down, q_rain, q_sno, S_atm_*) are interface passthroughs that downstream urban-canopy components consume via the upstream coupling.couple mechanism — they are preserved as parameters here to match the upstream component's external interface contract (the upstream `Structural Verification` test verifies the parameter set via `parameters(sys)`).\n\nEquation 1 (vapor pressure, Oleson Ch. 1 p.17): e_atm = q_atm * P_atm / (epsilon + (1-epsilon) * q_atm), where epsilon = MW_wv/MW_da. The Bolton-style mixing-ratio-to-vapor-pressure inversion. Singularities are non-physical: the denominator is bounded below by min(epsilon, 1-epsilon) = 0.378 for q_atm in [0,1], so the division is always well defined. At q_atm = 0, e_atm = 0 (dry air); as q_atm grows, e_atm approaches the asymptote q_atm * P_atm / (1-epsilon).\n\nEquation 2 (air density, Oleson Ch. 1 p.17): rho_atm = (P_atm - (1-epsilon) * e_atm) / (R_da * T_atm) — ideal-gas equation of state with humidity correction. Coupled to Eq. 1 via e_atm; the runner resolves them in the order Eq.1 → Eq.2.\n\nEquation 3 (reference height, Oleson Ch. 1 Footnote 1 p.16): z_atm = z_prime_atm + z_0 + z_d. The atmospheric model reports its reference height z'_atm above some local zero datum; the urban canopy uses an effective z_atm that includes the displacement height z_d (the height above which the log-law wind profile applies) and the roughness length z_0. Pure linear sum; no coupling to the thermodynamic state.\n\nObservability classification: this component is functionally observed-only — the three state variables are each given by a single algebraic equation in terms of parameters (the `(t)` time index on the upstream `@variables` has no role since there are no derivatives). Test scenarios use `time_span: [0, 1]` and sample at t=0 to mirror the convention used by sibling observed-only ESM files in this rig (surface_energy_flux.esm, heating_cooling_flux.esm, phase_change_energy.esm).\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1.0e-10): three observed-only algebraic equations (no ODE integration). Eq. 1 is one multiplication, one addition in the denominator, one division; Eq. 2 is one multiplication, one subtraction, one multiplication, one division; Eq. 3 is two additions. All operations are at IEEE-754 ULP precision (~1e-16). The upstream `Equation Verification - Vapor Pressure` and `Equation Verification - Reference Height` tests use `rtol = 1.0e-10`, matched here; `Equation Verification - Air Density` uses `rtol = 1.0e-6` because the upstream test rounded R_da to 287.042 in its analytical reference but lets the actual computed R_da (with full precision) drive the test — here the precomputed R_da default carries the full Julia-precision value, so the test compares full-precision to full-precision and we re-assert at rtol = 1.0e-10. Tighter `abs: 1e-12` is asserted on outputs that are exactly zero by construction (e.g. q_atm = 0 → e_atm = 0) so the assertion does not silently accept a stuck-at-zero regression."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-10
            },
            "variables": {
                "kappa_boltz": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/K",
                    "default": 1.38065e-23,
                    "description": "Boltzmann constant (Oleson Table 1.4) — upstream `@constants` κ_boltz; the per-particle gas constant for Avogadro-scaling the universal gas constant"
                },
                "N_A": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "mol^-1",
                    "default": 6.02214e23,
                    "description": "Avogadro's number (Oleson Table 1.4) — upstream `@constants` N_A; the conversion factor from per-mole to per-particle (Oleson uses kmol in the table; this value is converted to SI mol)"
                },
                "MW_da": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/mol",
                    "default": 0.028966,
                    "description": "Molecular weight of dry air (Oleson Table 1.4) — upstream `@constants` MW_da; standard atmospheric mean (Oleson reports 28.966 kg/kmol; here in SI kg/mol)"
                },
                "MW_wv": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/mol",
                    "default": 0.018016,
                    "description": "Molecular weight of water vapor (Oleson Table 1.4) — upstream `@constants` MW_wv; standard H2O molecular weight (Oleson reports 18.016 kg/kmol; here in SI kg/mol)"
                },
                "R_gas": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/(K*mol)",
                    "default": 8.314467591,
                    "description": "Universal gas constant R_gas = N_A * kappa_boltz (Oleson Table 1.4) — upstream `@constants` R_gas; the IEEE-754 double-precision product of the upstream Avogadro and Boltzmann defaults (matches Julia bit-for-bit). Not used in this component's equations but preserved as part of the upstream component's public constant interface"
                },
                "R_da": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "J/(K*kg)",
                    "default": 287.0423113650487,
                    "description": "Specific gas constant for dry air R_da = R_gas / MW_da (Oleson Table 1.4) — upstream `@constants` R_da; appears as the denominator scale of the ideal-gas law in Eq. 2 of this component. The IEEE-754 double-precision quotient of the upstream R_gas / MW_da defaults (matches Julia bit-for-bit, slightly tighter than the rounded 287.042 used in the upstream test docstring)"
                },
                "epsilon_ratio": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.6219705862045157,
                    "description": "Ratio of molecular weights epsilon = MW_wv / MW_da (Oleson Table 1.4) — upstream `@constants` ε_ratio; appears in the denominator of the vapor-pressure inversion (Eq. 1). The IEEE-754 double-precision quotient of MW_wv / MW_da (matches Julia bit-for-bit; commonly rounded to 0.622 in textbook references)"
                },
                "one_minus_epsilon": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.37802941379548427,
                    "description": "Complement 1 - epsilon = 1 - MW_wv / MW_da (Oleson Table 1.4) — upstream `@constants` one_minus_ε; appears as the coefficient of q_atm in the vapor-pressure denominator (Eq. 1) and as the coefficient of e_atm in the air-density numerator (Eq. 2). The IEEE-754 double-precision 1.0 - epsilon_ratio (commonly rounded to 0.378)"
                },
                "z_prime_atm": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 30.0,
                    "description": "Atmospheric reference height from the driving atmospheric model (Oleson Table 1.1) — z'_atm, the height above the zero datum at which the atmospheric forcing variables are reported. Combined with z_0 and z_d in Eq. 3 to produce the effective z_atm used by the urban-canopy flux computations"
                },
                "u_atm": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Zonal wind at the atmospheric reference height (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy momentum-flux components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "v_atm": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Meridional wind at the atmospheric reference height (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy momentum-flux components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "theta_atm": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 293.15,
                    "description": "Atmospheric potential temperature at the reference height (Oleson Table 1.1) — upstream `@parameters` θ_atm; passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy sensible-heat-flux components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "q_atm": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/kg",
                    "default": 0.01,
                    "description": "Specific humidity at the atmospheric reference height (Oleson Table 1.1) — input to the vapor-pressure inversion (Eq. 1) and indirectly the air-density correction (Eq. 2). Mass of water vapor per mass of moist air; typical mid-latitude values 0.001-0.02 kg/kg"
                },
                "P_atm": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "default": 101325.0,
                    "description": "Atmospheric pressure at the reference height (Oleson Table 1.1) — total pressure, input to both Eq. 1 (numerator of vapor-pressure inversion) and Eq. 2 (numerator of ideal-gas law). Default is the standard sea-level atmosphere (101325 Pa)"
                },
                "T_atm": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 293.15,
                    "description": "Atmospheric temperature at the reference height (Oleson Table 1.1) — input to the ideal-gas air-density equation (Eq. 2). Default is the standard sea-level temperature (293.15 K = 20 degC)"
                },
                "L_atm_down": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "W/m^2",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Incident downward longwave radiation at the reference height (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy longwave-flux components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "q_rain": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/(m^2*s)",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Liquid precipitation rate (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy hydrology components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "q_sno": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/(m^2*s)",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Solid precipitation rate (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy snow components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "S_atm_dir_vis": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "W/m^2",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Incident direct-beam visible solar radiation (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy shortwave-radiation components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "S_atm_dir_nir": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "W/m^2",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Incident direct-beam near-infrared solar radiation (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy shortwave-radiation components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "S_atm_dif_vis": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "W/m^2",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Incident diffuse visible solar radiation (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy shortwave-radiation components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "S_atm_dif_nir": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "W/m^2",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Incident diffuse near-infrared solar radiation (Oleson Table 1.1) — passthrough atmospheric forcing input consumed by downstream urban-canopy shortwave-radiation components; declared by the upstream interface component but not used in the three diagnostic equations of CLMUAtmosphere itself"
                },
                "z_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1.0,
                    "description": "Roughness length (Oleson Table 1.3, Footnote 1 p.16) — characteristic length scale of the surface drag for the log-law wind profile. Typical urban values 0.5-3 m. Input to Eq. 3 (effective reference height)"
                },
                "z_d": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 5.0,
                    "description": "Displacement height (Oleson Table 1.3, Footnote 1 p.16) — vertical offset of the log-law wind profile, representing the effective height of the canopy bulk drag center. Typical urban values 1-15 m (a fraction of building height H). Input to Eq. 3 (effective reference height)"
                },
                "e_atm": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "description": "Atmospheric vapor pressure (Oleson Ch. 1 p.17, Eq. 1): e_atm = q_atm * P_atm / (epsilon + (1-epsilon) * q_atm). Bolton-style inversion of specific humidity to vapor pressure for the moist-air state used by downstream flux components. At q_atm = 0 gives e_atm = 0; bounded above by P_atm at q_atm = 1"
                },
                "rho_atm": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "description": "Atmospheric air density (Oleson Ch. 1 p.17, Eq. 2): rho_atm = (P_atm - (1-epsilon) * e_atm) / (R_da * T_atm). Ideal-gas density of moist air, with the (1-epsilon)*e_atm correction subtracted from P_atm to give the dry-air partial pressure (which then divides by R_da*T_atm). The humidity correction makes moist air slightly less dense than dry air at the same P and T"
                },
                "z_atm": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Effective atmospheric reference height for flux computations (Oleson Ch. 1 Footnote 1 p.16, Eq. 3): z_atm = z_prime_atm + z_0 + z_d. Linear sum of the model-reported height and the surface drag-profile parameters; used by downstream urban-canopy momentum and turbulent-flux subcomponents as the height at which the atmospheric forcings are evaluated"
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "e_atm",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            { "op": "*", "args": ["q_atm", "P_atm"] },
                            {
                                "op": "+",
                                "args": [
                                    "epsilon_ratio",
                                    { "op": "*", "args": ["one_minus_epsilon", "q_atm"] }
                                ]
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "rho_atm",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "-",
                                "args": [
                                    "P_atm",
                                    { "op": "*", "args": ["one_minus_epsilon", "e_atm"] }
                                ]
                            },
                            { "op": "*", "args": ["R_da", "T_atm"] }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "z_atm",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "+",
                        "args": [
                            { "op": "+", "args": ["z_prime_atm", "z_0"] },
                            "z_d"
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "upstream_vapor_pressure_canonical",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream `Equation Verification - Vapor Pressure` test (UrbanCanopy.jl test/clmu_introduction_test.jl:71-99) at q_atm = 0.01 kg/kg, P_atm = 101325 Pa, T_atm = 293.15 K. Expected e_atm = 0.01 * 101325 / (0.6219705862 + 0.3780294138 * 0.01) = 1619.2546136658295 Pa (the upstream pre-computed reference). Anchors fidelity to the upstream Julia component at the same parameter values with rtol = 1.0e-10.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.01,
                        "P_atm": 101325.0,
                        "T_atm": 293.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 30.0,
                        "z_0": 1.0,
                        "z_d": 5.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "e_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1619.2546136658295,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upstream_vapor_pressure_dry_air",
                    "description": "Upstream secondary check from the same test (UrbanCanopy.jl test/clmu_introduction_test.jl:96-98): q_atm = 0 (perfectly dry air) gives e_atm = 0 exactly. The vapor-pressure numerator q_atm * P_atm vanishes; the denominator collapses to epsilon_ratio (non-zero) so the division is well defined. abs tolerance gates the stuck-at-zero failure mode and matches the upstream `atol = 1.0e-15` precision.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.0,
                        "P_atm": 101325.0,
                        "T_atm": 293.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 30.0,
                        "z_0": 1.0,
                        "z_d": 5.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "e_atm", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.0, "tolerance": { "abs": 1.0e-15 } }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upstream_air_density_dry",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream `Equation Verification - Air Density` test for dry air (UrbanCanopy.jl test/clmu_introduction_test.jl:101-123). At q_atm = 0, e_atm = 0 (from Eq. 1) so rho_atm = P_atm / (R_da * T_atm) = 101325 / (287.0423113650487 * 293.15) = 1.2041505695505632 kg/m^3 (the upstream pre-computed reference). Sister assertion confirms e_atm = 0 at the same point so the chain Eq.1 → Eq.2 is independently anchored.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.0,
                        "P_atm": 101325.0,
                        "T_atm": 293.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 30.0,
                        "z_0": 1.0,
                        "z_d": 5.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "e_atm",   "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.0, "tolerance": { "abs": 1.0e-15 } },
                        {
                            "variable": "rho_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.2041505695505632,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upstream_air_density_moist",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream `Equation Verification - Air Density` test for moist air (UrbanCanopy.jl test/clmu_introduction_test.jl:125-131): rho_atm = (101325 - 0.378 * 1619.25) / (287.042 * 293.15) = 1.1968760398898206 kg/m^3 (the upstream pre-computed reference at q_atm = 0.01). Anchors the (1-epsilon) * e_atm humidity-correction term in Eq. 2: moist air must be slightly less dense than dry air at the same P and T (1.1969 < 1.2042). This is the canonical 'moist air is less dense' check.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.01,
                        "P_atm": 101325.0,
                        "T_atm": 293.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 30.0,
                        "z_0": 1.0,
                        "z_d": 5.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "e_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1619.2546136658295,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "rho_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.1968760398898206,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upstream_reference_height",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream `Equation Verification - Reference Height` test (UrbanCanopy.jl test/clmu_introduction_test.jl:137-160) at z_prime_atm = 30 m, z_0 = 1 m, z_d = 5 m. Expected z_atm = 30 + 1 + 5 = 36 m exactly. Linear-sum identity (Eq. 3); no coupling to thermodynamic state.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.01,
                        "P_atm": 101325.0,
                        "T_atm": 293.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 30.0,
                        "z_0": 1.0,
                        "z_d": 5.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "z_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 36.0,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "qualitative_high_pressure_higher_density",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream `Qualitative Properties` check (test/clmu_introduction_test.jl:184-186): higher P_atm at same T_atm gives higher rho_atm (ideal-gas law monotonicity). At P_atm = 110000 Pa, q_atm = 0.01, T_atm = 293.15: e_atm scales linearly with P_atm (Eq. 1 numerator is q*P, denominator is q-only), so e_atm(110000) = 1757.8880582604613 Pa, then rho_atm = (110000 - one_minus_epsilon * e_atm) / (R_da * T_atm) = 1.2993472922564053 kg/m^3. Higher than the q=0.01, P=101325 reference rho = 1.1968760398898206 — the ideal-gas P/T scaling at constant T outweighs the moist-air correction.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.01,
                        "P_atm": 110000.0,
                        "T_atm": 293.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 30.0,
                        "z_0": 1.0,
                        "z_d": 5.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "e_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1757.8880582604613,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "rho_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.2993472922564053,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "qualitative_high_temperature_lower_density",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream `Qualitative Properties` check (test/clmu_introduction_test.jl:188-191): higher T_atm at same P_atm gives lower rho_atm. At T_atm = 313.15 K (40 degC), q_atm = 0.01, P_atm = 101325: e_atm is T-independent (Eq. 1 has no T term) so still 1619.2546136658295 Pa; rho_atm = (101325 - one_minus_epsilon * 1619.25) / (R_da * 313.15) = 1.1204349707606607 kg/m^3. Lower than the T = 293.15 reference rho = 1.1968760398898206 — matches the 1/T scaling of the ideal-gas law.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.01,
                        "P_atm": 101325.0,
                        "T_atm": 313.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 30.0,
                        "z_0": 1.0,
                        "z_d": 5.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "e_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1619.2546136658295,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        },
                        {
                            "variable": "rho_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 1.1204349707606607,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "qualitative_high_humidity_higher_vapor_pressure",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream `Qualitative Properties` check (test/clmu_introduction_test.jl:193-196): higher q_atm at same P_atm gives higher e_atm. At q_atm = 0.02, P_atm = 101325: e_atm = 0.02 * 101325 / (epsilon_ratio + one_minus_epsilon * 0.02) = 3219.062188099808 Pa. Strictly greater than the q = 0.01 reference e_atm = 1619.2546 Pa. Sublinear in q_atm: doubling q_atm gives slightly less than double e_atm because the denominator (1-epsilon)*q_atm grows alongside the numerator (asymptotically e_atm → q*P/(1-eps) ≈ q*P/0.378 as q→∞).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.02,
                        "P_atm": 101325.0,
                        "T_atm": 293.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 30.0,
                        "z_0": 1.0,
                        "z_d": 5.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "e_atm",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 3219.062188099808,
                            "tolerance": { "rel": 1.0e-10 }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "reference_height_zero_offsets",
                    "description": "Boundary case for Eq. 3: z_0 = z_d = 0 collapses the effective reference height to the raw atmospheric reference: z_atm = z_prime_atm + 0 + 0 = z_prime_atm. Confirms the linear-sum identity has no hidden offsets and pins the z_prime_atm passthrough behavior at the zero-surface limit (smooth bare ground).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "q_atm": 0.0,
                        "P_atm": 101325.0,
                        "T_atm": 293.15,
                        "z_prime_atm": 20.0,
                        "z_0": 0.0,
                        "z_d": 0.0
